<BlogPost
  title="Bib Mousse vs. Tubliss, Riding Pros and Cons"
  description=""
  category="Motorcycle Equipment"
  categorySlug="motorcycle-equipment"
>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2488" src="https://www.oregonmotorcyclerental.com/newsite/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-300x300.jpg 300w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-150x150.jpg 150w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-146x146.jpg 146w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-50x50.jpg 50w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-75x75.jpg 75w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-85x85.jpg 85w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder-80x80.jpg 80w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2016/12/0000-Neutech-The-TUbliss-Replacement-Bladder.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width:767px) 300px, 300px" />After many seasons, riding all sorts of different terrain several consistant traits have emerged. The Tubliss has definitivly replaced Tubes and Mousse for many riders. It offers a wide variety of pressure choices depending where and what you&#8217;re riding. I&#8217;ve run 0 lbs. pressure in the outer in extreme conditions, wet, slick no-traction kind of stuff and swear by the results. Mostly that means, beating my training partners up anything gnarly. It stays on the bead, and if installed correctly, lasts quite a long time. I usually check mine every 2 or 3 rides for pressure or possible leaks, and haven&#8217;t had many fail, until I began to use them in desert terrain. I&#8217;ve watched seasoned desert riders, me included, gash, and tear their tires on the sharp rocks found in all desert areas. Bib Mousse is my choice, when it comes to rocky stuff. They have a tendency to wobble, and come off the bead, but they never fail, and can&#8217;t flat. As they soften up the traction is almost Tubliss like. I get 3 tire changes out of them normally. Care is to be taken to loosen the straps on your bikes after you get home, as they will deform.</p>
